00:03:59.350 --> 00:04:04.920
but it's quite simple. First,
he recognizes that atoms in a metal

00:04:04.920 --> 00:04:10.490
are arranged in periodic positions.
There is an array. It's not just

00:04:10.490 --> 00:04:16.070
thrown together in some jumble.
So, atoms in solid set in regular

00:04:16.070 --> 00:04:21.640
patterns. We're going to learn
these patterns next week,

00:04:21.640 --> 00:04:27.210
arrays, and such solids where the
atoms are found in regular patterns

00:04:27.210 --> 00:04:31.660
are called crystals.
So, he took that as one benchmark.

00:04:31.660 --> 00:04:34.990
The second thing: he says that,
remember, Drude says that the

00:04:34.990 --> 00:04:38.330
valence electrons are free to move
around. And, he says,

00:04:38.330 --> 00:04:41.660
well, if these valence electrons are
free to move around,

00:04:41.660 --> 00:04:44.990
what would they be subjected to?
They would be subjected to a

00:04:44.990 --> 00:04:48.330
potential. This is how we derived
the energy levels in even a single

00:04:48.330 --> 00:04:51.660
hydrogen atom.
We've got the positive charge of

00:04:51.660 --> 00:05:11.986
the core; we've got the negative
charge of the electron.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:05:01.220
So, now I've got an electron,
and it sees the net positive charge

00:05:01.220 --> 00:05:07.440
of the atomic core.
But, it sees an array.

00:05:07.440 --> 00:05:13.660
It sees periodic variation in
potential. So,

00:05:13.660 --> 00:05:19.880
that's the second thing he says:
periodic potential acts on

00:05:19.880 --> 00:05:25.270
the valence electrons.
And then, he invokes wave mechanics.

00:05:25.270 --> 00:05:29.810
Remember, Schršdinger's equation
was only enunciated a couple years

00:05:29.810 --> 00:05:34.360
earlier, in 1926.
There's a Ph.D. student who hears

00:05:34.360 --> 00:05:38.900
about the Schršdinger equation as
applied to a gaseous atom.

00:05:38.900 --> 00:05:43.450
And, he's applying it to condensed
matter. And so,

00:05:43.450 --> 00:06:02.766
he solves the Schršdinger equation
with these constraints.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:57.460
And, what does he get?

00:05:57.460 --> 00:06:02.380
He gets a set of solutions.
He gets a family of solutions.

00:06:02.380 --> 00:06:07.300
And, these give rise to a set of
wavelengths of the electron that

00:06:07.300 --> 00:06:12.220
could move quickly through the
crystal, they could propagate.

00:06:12.220 --> 00:06:17.150
In other words, by invoking the
wavelength properties of the

00:06:17.150 --> 00:06:22.070
electron, he can rationalize how
these valence electrons can move

00:06:22.070 --> 00:06:40.606
through barriers that classical
physics would impose.

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:31.760
And so, pretty soon,
out falls electronic conductivity.

00:06:31.760 --> 00:06:36.530
So, this is pretty good for an
opening volley,

00:06:36.530 --> 00:06:41.300
not bad for a Ph.
. And, he eventually took on some

00:06:41.300 --> 00:06:46.070
