00:16:23.680 --> 00:16:41.326
this is the s-band.
But for magnesium,

00:16:08.500 --> 00:16:13.500
the p-band, the bottom of the p-band
lies below the top of the s-band.

00:16:13.500 --> 00:16:18.500
So, in the case of magnesium, this
is now the p-band.

00:16:18.500 --> 00:16:23.500
And, the p-band energy levels are
available so that when we fill the

00:16:23.500 --> 00:16:28.500
top of the s-band,
we can continue to move into a range

00:16:28.500 --> 00:16:33.500
of energy that allows for motion.
So, we are able to account for both

00:16:33.500 --> 00:16:38.500
unpaired electron atoms,
and paired electron atoms by this

00:16:38.500 --> 00:17:03.330
overlap of energies.
And, I think there's a cartoon in

00:17:03.330 --> 00:17:07.990
your reading that indicates that.
Yeah, this shows what happens with

00:17:07.990 --> 00:17:12.660
the energy levels as a function of
distance. And,

00:17:12.660 --> 00:17:17.330
you can see that the p-band is now
dropping below the top of the s-band,

00:17:17.330 --> 00:17:36.393
and so it allows for continuous
filling into more states.

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:06.000
And so, this now accounts for not
only such things as electrical

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:10.000
conductivity, but reflectivity.
Metals have luster because the

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:14.000
photons of visible light have the
capacity to excite electrons,

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:18.000
which immediately cascade down and
reflect back. So,

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:22.000
band theory became widespread in
popularity. In the 20s,

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:26.000
it was known only about a few
physicists. In the 30s,

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:30.000
the scientific community knew it.
In the 40s, it infected the popular

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:34.000
culture. If you talk to your
grandparents, they'll refer to the

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:38.000
40s as the big band era
because of this.

